And yes...there is the tracking id. So the webapp saves our id and give back a message when we come back again. Which means this part of the webapp must use the database, so probably we can use this tracking id to inject our sql code. Lets check it.
Intercept the request and change the id:
TrackingId=xlI6B96WIKSgh6Mx' OR '1'='1; >>> And it worked, we got a welcome back message! So we have a blind sql vulnerability...
"The database contains a different table called users, with columns called username and password. You need to exploit the blind SQL injection vulnerability to find out the password of the administrator user."
There is a method we can use to win out the adminstrator's password 1 by 1...
First lets see if there is a users table...
